# EMNIST Character Classification using CNN

## 📌 Overview

Built a Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) to classify handwritten characters (digits + uppercase + lowercase letters) using the EMNIST ByClass dataset.

✔ Multi-class classification (62 classes)
✔ Achieved ~83% test accuracy
✔ Handled dataset-specific preprocessing challenges

---

## 📂 Dataset

* Dataset: EMNIST (Extended MNIST)
* Source: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/crawford/emnist
* Total Classes: 62 (0–9, A–Z, a–z)
* Image Size: 28×28 (grayscale)

### ⚠️ Important Note

EMNIST images are **rotated and flipped by default**, which was corrected during preprocessing.

---

## ⚙️ Approach

### 1. Data Preprocessing

* Reshaped images to 28×28
* Fixed orientation:

  * Transpose
  * Horizontal flip
* Normalized pixel values (0–1)
* Added channel dimension (for CNN)

---

### 2. Model Architecture

```plaintext
Conv2D (32 filters) + ReLU  
Batch Normalization  
MaxPooling  

Conv2D (64 filters) + ReLU  
Batch Normalization  
MaxPooling  

Conv2D (128 filters) + ReLU  
Batch Normalization  
MaxPooling  

Flatten  
Dense (256) + ReLU  
Dropout (0.5)  

Output Layer (62 classes, Softmax)
```

---

### 3. Training

* Optimizer: Adam
* Loss: Sparse Categorical Crossentropy
* Epochs: 10
* Batch Size: 128

---

## 📊 Results

* Training Accuracy: ~84%
* Test Accuracy: ~83-84%

### 📈 Observations

* Model performs well on digits
* Confusion observed between similar characters:

  * O vs 0
  * l vs I
  * c vs C

---

## 🧠 Key Insights

* Small variations in handwritten characters significantly impact classification accuracy
* Proper preprocessing (orientation correction) is critical
* Increasing model depth improves performance but also risks overfitting

---

